[Although the cause of the deaths of the monkeys has not been determined yet, the lengthy discussion of yellow fever (YF) and the steps being taken to increase surveillance and preparation for an anticipated outbreak suggest that YF is suspected. ProMED will be interested in any results that come from the cases under investigation.

Brazil has cases of YF during the seasons for sylvan (forest) transmission of the virus. Deaths of monkey are often indicators that the virus is circulating in a given area. There were major YF outbreaks in several states of Brazil during the 2016-2017 and 2017-2018 seasons. A recent WHO report indicates that in the current 2018-2019 season (July 2018 to March 2019), a total of 75 confirmed human cases, including 17 deaths (case fatality rate = 23%), have been reported in Brazil in the states of Sao Paulo (62 cases), Parana (12), and Santa Catarina (1). That same report indicates that 33 confirmed epizootics (cases in non-human primates) were reported in 5 federal states: Sao Paulo (20), Rio de Janeiro (8), Minas Gerais (1), Mato Grosso (2), and Parana (2). In the 4 weeks preceding this report, epizootics have been confirmed in Sao Paulo and Parana states (see Yellow fever - Americas (07): Brazil, WHO 20190419.6432053). - Mod.TY

